To allow your users to sign in with Google and potentially upgrade their anonymous account to a Google account, follow these general steps:

1. First, be sure you have correctly integrated Firebase Authentication into your Android app, and added the necessary dependencies to your `build.gradle` file.

2. Set up the Google Sign-In method in the Firebase console:
    - Go to the Firebase Console.
    - Select your project.
    - Navigate to the "Authentication" section.
    - Click on the "Sign-in method" tab.
    - Enable Google Sign-In and configure the OAuth consent screen by providing the necessary information.

3. Add the Google sign-in dependency in your `build.gradle` file:
```gradle
implementation 'com.google.android.gms:play-services-auth:19.2.0'
```

4. Now, in your Java code, you should configure Google Sign-In to request the user's ID, email address, and profile. Here's an example of how you might do this:
```java
GoogleSignInOptions gso = new GoogleSignInOptions.Builder(GoogleSignInOptions.DEFAULT_SIGN_IN)
        .requestIdToken(getString(R.string.default_web_client_id))
        .requestEmail()
        .build();
```
The string `R.string.default_web_client_id` refers to your Web client ID which you can get from your Firebase project settings. It should be included in your `strings.xml` file.

5. Next, you should create a `GoogleSignInClient` instance:
```java
GoogleSignInClient mGoogleSignInClient = GoogleSignIn.getClient(this, gso);
```

6. Now initiate the Google SignIn flow:
```java
// Build a GoogleSignInClient with the options specified by gso.
mGoogleSignInClient = GoogleSignIn.getClient(this, gso);

// ...

Intent signInIntent = mGoogleSignInClient.getSignInIntent();
startActivityForResult(signInIntent, RC_SIGN_IN);
```
Make sure to define `RC_SIGN_IN` as a constant that you'll use to identify the sign-in intent result.

7. In your `onActivityResult`, handle the sign-in result:
```java
@Override
public void onActivityResult(int requestCode, int resultCode, Intent data) {
    super.onActivityResult(requestCode, resultCode, data);

    // Result returned from launching the Intent from GoogleSignInApi.getSignInIntent(...);
    if (requestCode == RC_SIGN_IN) {
        Task<GoogleSignInAccount> task = GoogleSignIn.getSignedInAccountFromIntent(data);
        try {
            // Google Sign In was successful, authenticate with Firebase
            GoogleSignInAccount account = task.getResult(ApiException.class);
            firebaseAuthWithGoogle(account);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            // Google Sign In failed
        }
    }
}
```

8. When you have a `GoogleSignInAccount` object, you can authenticate with Firebase:
```java
private void firebaseAuthWithGoogle(GoogleSignInAccount acct) {
    AuthCredential credential = GoogleAuthProvider.getCredential(acct.getIdToken(), null);

    mAuth.getCurrentUser().linkWithCredential(credential)
            .addOnCompleteListener(this, new OnCompleteListener<AuthResult>() {
                @Override
                public void onComplete(@NonNull Task<AuthResult> task) {
                    if (task.isSuccessful()) {
                        // Sign in success, update UI with the signed-in user's information
                        FirebaseUser user = task.getResult().getUser();
                        // User has been linked to the Google account
                    } else {
                        // If sign in fails, display a message to the user.
                        // This is also where we will check if the account already exists with another sign-in method
                        if (task.getException() instanceof FirebaseAuthUserCollisionException) {
                            // Handle the scenario when the user already exists (e.g., log in instead of link)
                        }
                        // Update your UI here accordingly.
                    }
                }
            });
}
```

This process links the anonymous account to the Google account. If the link is successful, the user's anonymous account and the new credential (from Google) are merged, and the user can continue with their Google account where they left off with their anonymous account.

Keep in mind that this solution outlines the happy path. You'll want to make sure your app handles exceptions and various auth states correctly, like when a sign-in collision occurs (when the Google account being used to sign up has already been linked to another Firebase Auth account).

In addition, add the necessary checks and UI prompts to guide users through the upgrade process smoothly. For instance, if you detect that the anonymous user has important data that might be lost, you should prompt them to upgrade the account before proceeding with other tasks.

When the user hits the Sign In with Google button, you'll want to start the Google sign-in process by launching the sign-in intent you've created using your `GoogleSignInClient` instance. Here is what you should do in your button's click listener:

1. Define the `RC_SIGN_IN` constant. This is the request code you'll use to identify the sign-in result in `onActivityResult`.

```java
private static final int RC_SIGN_IN = 9001;
```

2. Set up the click listener for your Google sign-in button. When the button is clicked, you start the sign-in process.

```java
// In your activity or fragment, where you have your button set up:
Button signInButton = findViewById(R.id.sign_in_button); // Assuming your button has the ID sign_in_button
signInButton.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    @Override
    public void onClick(View v) {
        Intent signInIntent = mGoogleSignInClient.getSignInIntent();
        startActivityForResult(signInIntent, RC_SIGN_IN);
    }
});
```

3. Make sure that your `onActivityResult` method is set up to handle the sign-in intent results.

```java
@Override
public void onActivityResult(int requestCode, int resultCode, Intent data) {
    super.onActivityResult(requestCode, resultCode, data);

    // Result returned from launching the Intent from GoogleSignInApi.getSignInIntent(...);
    if (requestCode == RC_SIGN_IN) {
        Task<GoogleSignInAccount> task = GoogleSignIn.getSignedInAccountFromIntent(data);
        try {
            // Google Sign In was successful, authenticate with Firebase
            GoogleSignInAccount account = task.getResult(ApiException.class);
            firebaseAuthWithGoogle(account);
        } catch (ApiException e) {
            // Google Sign In failed, update UI appropriately
            // ...
        }
    }
}
```

With this setup, when the Sign In with Google button is clicked, the Google sign-in flow begins, and the user will be presented with the account chooser or sign-in prompts. Once the user has successfully signed in with their Google account, the `firebaseAuthWithGoogle` method (which you should have implemented following the previous instructions) will be called to authenticate with Firebase and link the anonymous account to the Google account.

